<p>The <a href="/images/DouglasBaderParkBallot.pdf">infopack</a> given to residents of the Douglas Bader Park estate contains a similar threat:</p>

<p><img src="/images/DouglasBaderParkBallot.png" alt="" /></p>

<p>This becoming a common element when it comes to estate regeneration ballots. Certain options are taken off the table when it comes to the ballot paper and residents are told to vote for full redevelopment or face many more years of running the estate down. Refurbishment or scheduled maintenance as usual are simply not presented as an option.</p>

<p>This, coupled with incentives to tenants like the offer of an extra bedroom if they are overoccupying or offers of secure tenancies to licencess has become a winning formula for Councilâ€™s looking to gain tenantsâ€™ support for their schemes.</p>

<p>The Mayorâ€™s policy guidance on ballots specifically says that refurbishment needs to be an option but it would appear he is turning a blind eye to what is becoming a common practice in the regeneration game.</p>
